# Testing Standards

Lineup uses three tiers of tests. Each has its own standards document.

| Tier | Purpose | Location | Standards |
|------|---------|----------|-----------|
| **Unit** | Single function/module in isolation | `src/__tests__/`, `server/__tests__/` | `unit-testing-standards` rule |
| **Integration** | Modules working together (routes + middleware) | `server/__tests__/integration/` | `integration-testing-standards` rule |
| **E2E** | Full user flows in a real browser | `e2e/` | `e2e-testing-standards` rule |

## Choosing the Right Tier

- Testing a pure function? → **Unit test**
- Testing an API route with middleware? → **Integration test**
- Testing what a user sees and does? → **E2E test**

## Shared Conventions

- `describe`/`it` blocks with descriptive names. `it` starts with a verb.
- Factory helpers (e.g. `makeEvent()`) for test data — no inline object literals repeated across tests.
- Deterministic data — no `new Date()` without fake timers, no `Math.random()`.
- Never mock the function under test.
- Never weaken assertions to make tests pass (see `self-healing-tests` rule).

## Running Tests

```bash
# Unit + integration (app)
cd tv-guide-app && npx jest --no-coverage

# Unit + integration (server)
cd tv-guide-app/server && npx jest --no-coverage

# E2E
cd tv-guide-app && npx playwright test
```

## Pre-Push Rule

**Always run unit and server tests before pushing.** No exceptions.

```bash
cd tv-guide-app && npx jest --no-coverage
cd tv-guide-app && npx jest --config server/jest.config.ts --no-coverage
```

**E2E tests**: Only run locally when E2E test files (`e2e/*.spec.ts`) have been added or modified. CI runs them on every push regardless, so they always gate merges. Don't run them just because app code changed -- they're slow and CI covers it.

If any test fails, fix it before pushing. Do not push broken code and rely on CI to catch it.

## CI

All tests run automatically on push to `main` and on pull requests (see `.github/workflows/test.yml`). The workflow has separate jobs for app unit, server unit, server integration, E2E, and coverage thresholds — each visible as its own check in GitHub.

- If CI fails but tests pass locally, check for non-determinism: `new Date()` without mocking, OS-specific paths, or timing-dependent assertions.
- Never merge with red CI. Fix the tests or the code first.
- Never add `[skip ci]` to commit messages to bypass test failures.
